segments.text: This is Terry Anderson, and we are testing the 4th of May, 1982.
Testing, testing, today's date is May 4th, 1983.
We are trying to find out if we need a microphone.
Okay, okay.
that that higher ranking guy at the appropriate time will step forward when they're ready to fill a position that says, I've got the man that needs to go in that position.
In other words, he's in a position to act as your ombudsman.
He maneuvers you into positions where you can accept more responsibility and thus stand a better chance of being promoted.
I think from that standpoint that it would be human nature for a West Point graduate or an Air Force Academy graduate

by his associations with people from that same institution would be more likely to latch on to one of those bright and shining young guys to maneuver him than it would be somebody from some other place.
By the same token, I think the same would be true for Texas A&M.
I know a lot of pretty high-ranking guys.
General Wayman Nutt, who's a two-star over at San Antonio right now, met him at a meeting not long ago.
We weren't together three minutes before we had already found out several people we knew of each other.
Almost instant rapport established because of our commonality of our background.
And so when the time comes, he's going to be looking at people like that, people that he knows, to plug in where they need to be plugged in.
So yes, it's an advantage from that standpoint.
through the association and his knowing your background, then he'd be in a position to push you when the time comes.
What class is he?
Wayman is, I believe he's the class of 49.
How do you spell his last name?
N-U-T-T, Wayman Nutt.
He's the commander of the San Antonio Air Logistics Center.
Got about 23,000 people working for him over there.
He's a two-star.
Heck of a knife.
And he's still on active?
Still on active duty.
That's why I haven't heard of him.
When you compare the officers from the Academy versus the officers from A&M, would you say one is better or less prepared or better prepared?
Once again, I really haven't had that much contact with the Academy graduates.
Most of them, of course, are in the Army, and I've always been in the Air Force.
Yeah, but I mean even ever since they built the Air Force Academy.
Yeah.
I would say they're comparable.
I really would.
I think they're pretty well comparable.
They've got a lot in common.
So I really wouldn't think that...

I would think by the very nature that your graduate of the service academy, whichever service it may be, Annapolis, West Point, Air Force, is going to have to give you some, just a little bit of an edge on someone that did not go there.
And I think we all accept that.
But that's not to say that you can't overcome that through other actions.
OK, now during the interview, we've talked about people who've had some impact on your life.
And I was wondering if any, while you were at A&M taking classes and in the Corps, if there were any of the professional soldiers here who had an impact on you, or any of the professors?
Yes.
There was a guy that was the assistant commandant at the time.
I was a sophomore here, the name of Taylor Wilkins.
At the height of the Korean War, I was doing very poorly academically.
I was on probation and very near getting kicked out of A&M for scholastic problems.
I was spending all my time in the Corps activity.
We didn't do anything that I wasn't there because I loved it.
As a result, I neglected my schoolwork.
This was after I changed my major from petroleum engineering to business.
And I really liked what I was doing.
It's just that I didn't have enough time to do it all.
And the Corps came first with me.
mother and dad were concerned that with the Korean War in full flower, that I was going to flunk out and that I was going to get drafted in the Air Force, that they wanted me to be in the Air Force.

So they came down and we all had talked and apparently an Air Force recruiter had gotten a hold of them and said, you know, if you can get him on in here now, we can put him in the Air Force and he can be an enlisted guy in the Air Force.
And so
That made sense to me because I knew I was just really having a rough time staying in school.
So we went to see Taylor Wilkins.
And he sat down and talked with my father, my mother, and myself for two hours, I guess, and just flat talked us out of the whole thing.
He said, look, you can do it.
He gave me a lot of positive thinking kind of thing.
Don't think you're going to flunk out.
Think you're going to stay and do what it takes to make it.
And that was kind of a turning point for me.
So I went ahead and stayed in A&M.
And sure enough, I did make my probation.
And I was able to stay in and eventually graduate.
But we were within minutes of me resigning from A&M and joining the Air Force as an enlisted guy.
And Wilkins, Taylor Wilkins, had the insight to see that that was going to be a mistake, that I could make it.
I had the potential to make it if I just worked at it.
And he told me, you know.
So you get some demerits and have to walk the bullring.
Don't spend so much time on your shoes.
Don't spend so much time on your brass.
Start spending more time studying.
And I did.
And it paid off.
So I would have to say that I wouldn't be here right now if it weren't for Taylor Wilkins.
What happened to him?
He later left and went to Allen Academy, which is a local military academy in town, as their commandant.
And then he died.
I think he had a heart attack or something.
I don't know just why.

I was never real close to Colonel Wilkins other than the fact that I knew who he was, and he took enough interest in me to spend that couple hours with me and my mother and father to tell us what he thought.
And we listened to him.
That's one time we listened to a guy that was right, and we were wrong.
How about professors here?
Oh, my.
I remember the hardest course I ever had was statistics, and we had a guy by the name of Miles Hamilton.
Everybody had nicknames then, and I guess they still do.
But Dr. Hamilton was my statistics professor.
There's a professor here that had a great deal of impact on me, gave me a lot of inspiration.
He's still here, by the way.
He's a salesmanship or marketing professor named Herb Thompson in the College of Business Administration.
Herb's always been a good friend of mine, and he gave me a lot of encouragement.
I made some good grades under him.
There was a gentleman that doesn't teach here anymore, but he was a business law professor, and he's still a practicing attorney here in town named Phil Goode.
Phil was a
Great inspiration.
He always liked me, and I liked him, and he gave me a lot of encouragement.
I did well in some of his classes.
By the time you were about a junior then, were you picking your grades up?
Yeah, right.
My sophomore year was my bad year.
Keep in mind that when I changed my major, I changed it at the middle of my freshman year, and I had a whole bunch of F's.
bad, bad Fs.
And I had all that to overcome.
So my sophomore year was kind of the year that I turned around.
And then my junior and senior year, I picked up and did pretty well.
What was the feeling among the student body toward the war in Korea?
I mean, did a lot of them decide, let's quit going to college and go over there and fight?
Did they think it would be better for them to stay here and become officers?
That was the general opinion.
Most of us felt that it was something that might go on for a while and that we could best serve our country and ourselves by staying in school, getting a commission, and then going.
As it worked out, when I graduated, I had a set of orders for Yokohama, Japan.
I was reported to Yokohama and then for further assignment into the Korean area.
But almost exactly the same thing happened with me as happened with my father.
I'd already received my orders to report to the port of embarkation, and the war ended.
And so I've never served one day overseas.
After all these years, I've never served one day of overseas assignments.
You can see it's all been stateside.
And so I've got mixed emotions about that.
Nobody wants to be in a conflict, or no one wants to be in combat.
But I kind of feel, you know, I almost have guilt feelings that here
I'm a brigadier general, and I've never seen any combat.
I guess it's dumb to say I feel guilty about that, but when I think of the prices that some other generals have paid, I really feel like I hadn't really earned it.
But apparently someone thinks I have, or I wouldn't be there.
That is very interesting.
Now, when you were about ready to graduate,
When did you make up your mind that you wanted to go into the military?
Or was the military going to help you by taking you anyway?
I didn't have any choice.
There was no choice to be made.
At that time, I had two years active duty and six years in reserves as an obligation to my accepting the contract.
That was a two-year contract.
I spent two years on active duty.
I married...
my wife between my junior and senior year in August before my senior year.
So I was married my senior year.
And then did you move to a married dormitory?
We moved into an off-campus apartment, which is still here, just over on the south side on Montclair Street.
And so my wife and I, of course, were in the service together.
We liked it pretty well.
At the end of the two years active duty hitch, we just decided that we didn't want to make a career out of it.
And so I was on a military leave from Sears Roebuck.
I went to work for Sears Roebuck right after I graduated and worked for them for a short time and then went on active duty for two years.
And so I had returned privileges with Sears.
And so I went back to work for Sears and worked for them for a number of years.
But this must have had a pretty big impact on you going into the active duty when you had thought about the military for many years.
You'd loved the Corps.
You'd liked the regimentation.
And you liked all the military aspects of the Corps.
Were you let down when you really got to the real thing, the US military?
Or is let down too strong?
Disillusioned in some way?
I can't really, neither of those words fit.
I was surprised, I think might be a better word.
It was more like a day's work.
It was kind of a business.
People worked eight to five a month through Friday and they went home.
And that just wasn't really the way I'd envisioned it.
But it was such a much more relaxed pace than I was used to.
I was used to spit and polish at a certain time, a certain time.
When I got on active duty, everybody was kind of laid back.
And we had a job to do, and we did it.
My active duty outfit was with an air evacuation outfit.
It was a hospital-type airplane where we evacuated and moved sick patients from one part of the country to another.
And I was a supply officer.
was not able to go to flying school because of my eyesight.
It's always been poor.
And at those times, you had to have a 20-20 vision before they would let you go to pilot school.
And so I've never flown an airplane.
I couldn't fly one now if I had to.
I've never been to pilot training.
But anyway, I was a supply officer for this air evacuation outfit and really enjoyed it.
a two-year hitch.
Part of that time I was at Lackland in processing and getting in, and part of the time after that I went to Cheyenne, Wyoming to supply school, which was a six-week school, as I recall.
So I really wasn't on active duty at the station at Mobile, Alabama, Brooke Air Force Base, which has since been decommissioned.
The base is no longer there, but it was a big air material area center at that time.
They now call them air logistics centers.
At that time, they called them AMLAs, Air Material Areas.
And Mobile Air Material Area was where I was stationed at Brookie Air Force Base Mobile.
But it was quite a change from what I, it wasn't anything at all like I expected.
Well, I don't, again, don't want to put words in your mouth, but it sounds like you were maybe a little bit too energetic
and driving for the peacetime Air Force.
Is that true?
Not really 100%.
What would you explain?
There was enough challenge there, but I was bored at times.
There was not enough to keep me busy all day every day.
I'd find myself going to the gym and shooting goals because all my work would be done by coffee break in the morning.
I was a little bit, I've always been the type that I like to be behind all the time.
I like to always have something that's waiting for me that needs to be done.
And of course in the job I have now, that's no problem.
But I was really kind of bored in the Air Force.
I really was.
And I know that's a problem we have today in the Air Force.
A lot of people are in jobs that they just don't have enough to do.
And so I try to
remedy that any time I find it.
But I think that had probably a lot to do with my deciding to get off active duty.
What about your wife?
What was her feelings?
She just never was really as gung-ho military as I was.
She was raised in the oil field.
Her father was an oil field worker.

and uh west texas or east uh mostly south america venezuela primarily and so she had spent a lot of her time in a of course a south american oil camp is somewhat like a military camp in that you've got perimeter fence bob wire on top guard on the gate uh you've got a camp boss that's kind of like a base commander yeah and a lot of regimentation and so she she just uh never did really go that crazy about the military
And so I think we were both pretty well ready to get off active duty.
Of course, I had to stay in the reserve six years because that was part of my obligation.
But by the end of that six years, I was really hooked on the reserve program.
I've always felt that it was a worthwhile program, the citizen-soldier type approach.
The war in this country have always been fought by the masses of people that are grocerymen and service station people and plumbers and carpenters.
It's never been ready.
fought by career people.
That's just the nucleus.
Of course, the problem we're faced with now, the next war we have is going to become a UR war.
We're not going to have time to train the bakers and grocerymen and so forth.
And so I think we're in a more dangerous environment today than we've ever been.
Because of the time that's left?
Because of that, and plus because of the very short time frame that all of our war plans call for.
We're looking at three-day wars, seven-day wars.
If it's a long war, it might last 30 days.
Whereas before, we're talking about years and years and years.
We'll never see those kinds of wars again.
Because of technology.
Yes.
Now, I'm not saying that we can't have an El Salvador or something like that that could draw on for years.
That's not what I'm talking about.
I'm talking about an all-out war.
where the entire resources of this nation are thrown into it.
We'll never have a war like that that will last very long because of the nature of the conflict.
It'll be over very quickly.
And nobody will win, of course.
Well, after two years out of active duty, you decided to return to reserve status.
Tell me about the reserves in the mid-1950s, and why did you become so hooked on them after your six-year obligation?
I think probably a lot of the same reasons that I enjoyed the Corps so much.
It was a group of guys, got to be real close to them.
A lot of them are still around town here.
We had what we felt to be an important job, that is to be ready to be called in case we were needed, with next to zero money and next to zero equipment to train and operate with.
It was kind of a challenge, really.
It's kind of like the old boy's got camping trips.
He used to go and live off the land.

Then, of course, I've been in the Air Force Reserve Program long enough to watch it go from the days where you watch the Air Force story on film over and over down in the basement of the post office building with zero equipment up to the point now that we're getting F-16s off the assembly line.
It has just been marvelous to watch the growth of the Reserve Program.
And we're really a viable force now.
Whereas before, all we could be would be fillers for active duty units.
Now, the Air Force Reserve really is split into two different areas.
One is what we call the unit program, which means that we have numbered flag-carrying units that can go to war as a unit.
military airlift wings, fighter wings, and so forth, F-16s.
We've got A-10s and all kinds of different planes and units that can go to war and function as a unit independently of everybody else if we had to.
Then we have the other portion, which is the portion that I'm involved with now.
I've always been in the unit program up until just a short time ago, but we have what we call the Individual Mobilization Assistance, IMAs.
We are fillers for active duty units.
We train with the active duty units.
In the event of mobilization, we know exactly where we go, exactly who we'll be working with, even where our desk is.
I've got a desk right now with all my junk in it at Tinker Air Force Base, Oklahoma City.
So if I was called active duty, if I were called active duty, I could be there in less than 24 hours.
We have to be there in less than 24 hours.
And so I keep my bag packed all the time, ready to be packed.
And I'll be leaving at 4 o'clock tomorrow afternoon to go up for three days.
My boss is a two-star general.
Just got promoted to three, by the way.
I'm losing him.
He's going to be commander of 15th Air Force at Mars Air Force Base at Riverside, California.
So I'll be breaking in a new boss.
What is his job now?
He's the commander of Oklahoma City Air Logistics Center.
I mentioned Wayman Nutt at San Antonio, Commander of San Antonio Air Logistics Center.
Well, this is another air logistics center.

We have one at Sacramento, California, one at San Antonio, one at Oklahoma City, one at Robbins Air Force Base, Georgia, and then the headquarters for Air Force Logistics Command at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base at Dayton, Ohio.
So there are five logistics centers, air logistics centers, and he's the commander of one of them.
and that's a two-star slot.
So now he's getting his own Air Force.
He's getting his own numbered Air Force, 15th Air Force at March Air Force Base, and his third star.
He gets them both on the 1st of September.
See, I was mentioning to you that you had to have a sponsor.
He's already making overtures that when his two-star logistics officer slot opens up that he wants me to come out and take that.
So in other words, it's people you meet that you do a good job for, and then when the time comes,
and he needs a reservist, well, then he'll think of me.
So in other words, that's the way.
But that would be a reserve position.
It would be a reserve position.
And it's to augment the activity force.
Basically, the concept is that they're on a two-shift operation now.
They have a morning shift and a swing shift.
Well, in the event of mobility, then they'd add the third shift, the graveyard shift, and then that would be the one that I would take.
I would be the actual commander during an eight-hour portion of the day for that air logistics center.

And we have 22,000 civilians, and we have responsibilities for, well, the new B-1 bombers, all the maintenance on the new B-1, on the B-52, on the KC-135, on the A-10, on the A-7, plus about half the engines in the Air Force.
We have maintenance responsibility for those, plus supply responsibilities for a whole bunch of things.
And so then I would be beefing that command operation up.
But I'm part of the command section.
Wherever the commander goes, I go.
When I go, I get my staff car with the star on the bumper, and my office is right next to his.
And I'm part of the real Air Force for the three days that I'm up there this week.
That's fantastic.
And it's just like being on active duty.
And what did this program, these two different programs, IMA and the unit program, when did they develop?
I would say the unit program has been around for a long time.
I would say the unit program probably is 15 years old or so.
So during the Vietnamese?
Yes.
I would say the IMA program probably is seven or eight years old.
Basically what it amounted to is a lot of people
Normally the unit program doesn't have very much rank in it because, you know, you take a wing commander as a brigadier general.
A group commander usually is a full colonel.

Well, after you get up to that point, you're still young, you've got a lot of time to go, but if you get promoted, say, from lieutenant colonel to a colonel, and there's not a group open, you know, you get promoted out of a job is what it amounts to.
So they started looking around.
With all this talent, all these years of experience, we don't want that guy to walk out the door.
What kind of a program can we put together so the Air Force can utilize his talents, his past training, and his experience, and what have you, without losing that resource?
So they came up with the Individual Mobilization Program, which enables him to mesh in with an existing active duty outfit and just augment that unit.
I think all branches of the service have the program now.
Oh, and was the Air Force the first to develop it?
That I don't know.
I don't know who pirated the concept.
I just don't know who originated it, really.
But it seems to be working very well.
Fantastic.
So I would say at Oklahoma City, and of course, I'm the ranking reservist there as a brigadier, we have about seven full colonels.
And with all the ranks combined, we have close to 300 reserves assigned to that air logistics center.
Mm-hmm.
And that includes enlisted ranks also.
So in other words, if the whistle blows, that organization will have to really get into high gear, start turning out planes.
much more quickly than it has been in the past.
So we've got a ready trained pool of people to put in there.
And we've got people right down the line twisting wrenches.
You can go in there and you won't know which is reserves and which is active duty.
Just like on active duty when you can't tell.
That's right.
So it's an exciting time to be in a reserve program.
Well, let's go back to the 1950s.
And let's talk a little bit about those six years.
What time is it?
I've got 4.15, and I'm going to need to wind up by 4.30, because I've got to get a haircut before the barbershop closes.
We can stop right now.
Today's June 14th.
This is the second interview with General Cargill.
I was interested in, I noticed on your resume that you spent about 10 years from 57 to 67 with one or two exceptions as a supply officer for the reserves.
And I was wondering about any particular problems you might have had in the supply field with procuring certain types of goods.
Were there shortages in certain goods?
Could you talk about that?
I would say that
Historically, we had the same problems during that time period that we have today, and that is shortage of funds with which to buy the things.
The goods and the products and the parts and what have you have always been there if you had the money to buy them.
Now, there's long lead times, especially on aircraft parts and especially on aircraft that are getting old where
let's say that they're not making the aircraft anymore, but still they have a parts obligation.
They won't tool up and make eight or ten parts.
If they tool up, they're going to make a thousand at one time.
Really, when you're talking about supply, you're talking about basically two types of supplies.
You're talking about maintenance or housekeeping or personal type supplies like field jackets and cold weather gear and
and office supplies and things like that.
The other type we refer to as a category is tech supply or technical supplies, which is another way of saying aircraft parts and aircraft related supply items.
The priority between how much money goes to which of these different sectors depends on a whole lot of factors, primarily the world conditions at the time.
Right now,
We're placing emphasis on technical supply, sustainability of aircraft, rapid turnaround in maintenance facilities, so technical supplies or parts for aircraft have the highest priority right now.
And it fluctuates through year in and year out, depending on what the imperatives are at the time.
And I would imagine that it fluctuates from administration to administration.
Yes, it does.
Very definitely.
Would you talk about that?
I really haven't been that close to it on active duty.
And of course, reservists don't get involved much in the day-to-day management.

But just from a more than interested casual observer, it's evident that right now, for example, under Ronald Reagan's administration, and with the emphasis that the DOD is getting and the money that the DOD is getting, that we're going to do much better as far as readiness is concerned.
than we have under past administrations.
Carter's specifically was disastrous as far as the readiness is concerned.
But you take the dollars you have and allocate them as best you can and stretch them as far as they'll go.
But there's never a day since I've been connected with the Air Force been enough dollars.
And I don't really expect there will be.
And I'm not sure it'd be a healthy thing if we did have all the dollars we needed for ever
thing we had because too many other programs would be lacking.
It's a balance.
Yeah, absolutely.
In what way did the war in Vietnam have an impact on your job as a reserve supply officer?
I really didn't feel that much of an impact.
The war in Vietnam escalated very slowly.
It was a very long, drawn out,
war, there was not a sudden declaration of war, complete mobilization.
So it was such a gradual thing.
And since my particular activity was not called active duty, I really didn't notice it as far as any impact it had on me as reservist.
Of course, obviously, we were all intensely interested in what was happening.
But how it changed my way of doing business, it didn't really at all.
In other words, the reserve people were slighted because the active duty people were getting more of the supply?
No, because at that time, we weren't getting anything anyway.
Oh, I see.
We really didn't start getting what I consider an adequate share of the funding and equipment until really after the Vietnamese War was over.
I think after the Vietnamese War was over,

That's when the reserve really began to come into their own because the people in authority realized at that time that a reservist could be trained and ready to go to war and in the same state of readiness for a fraction of what it would cost to sustain a full-time active duty officer or airman to do the same job.
So it was strictly a matter of dollars and cents.
You can get more bang for the buck, so to speak, from a reserve activity than you can from an active duty activity, because they don't fly as much.
Now, they don't train as much per month, but they train for longer periods of time.
In the unit program, the flying program, where we have our aircraft, you might, on an active duty outfit, you might have a young first lieutenant
that's been on active duty for a year and a half, maybe two years.
He just got out of flight school, and he's out doing his thing.
Back in the reserve unit, you might have a captain or a major that's been flying that same airplane for 12, 15 years.
The age and maturity and experience, we always do extremely well in competition with active duty outfits and shoot-offs and things like that where they have gunnery competition.
Reserves nearly always come in high or win them just outright.
And so basically we don't do it as often, but we've done it for such a much longer period of time that that maturity and training really pays off for us.
Okay, I want to ask you about, do you think it was a mistake that, and some critics have said that it was a mistake that LBJ did not call up the reserves.
I'd like your opinion on that, but I want to check.
Now, in what time period are you speaking about?
Well, we're talking about 1965 and 66 when many people said that during the Vietnamese War, instead of increasing the draft,
instead of increasing the draft, what he should do is he should use this pool of very qualified reservists and send them to Vietnam.
What do you feel about that?
I feel that he made the right decision basically for this reason.
The reserves are your last resort.
When you call the reserves, that's your trump card.
You've got nothing left.
Now, depending on the timing of the situation, you may have to play that trump card.
In his situation, he didn't have to play that trump card due to the gradual escalation and buildup and so forth.
So my personal opinion is that the reserve should be exactly that, held in reserve until your other alternatives have been exhausted.
Full declaration of war then?
Not necessarily.
As I mentioned yesterday when we were talking, in my opinion, any future conflict where we really get down to it
there's not going to be enough time to mobilize, to train, to send the tech school to man active duty outfits.
I think the likelihood for reserve units being activated in the future are much, much higher than they've ever been in the history of the reserve program.
There's no question that if things escalate,
whether it's a declared war, whether it's a police action, what have you, that a lot of reserve units are going to be activated.
For that reason, we have a lot of trouble.
A lot of people know that.

And for that reason, we have, up until the recession came along, have had a lot of trouble recruiting people, especially in some particular type outfits that are particularly vulnerable to activation.
For example, an airport squadron.
which is a unit that helps load and unload airplanes at ports of embarkation, shipping freight, and things like that.
Over half of the Air Force's capability for that type of activity is in the reserve program.
So if they surge, there's only one place they can get trained people, and that's by activating some reserve outfits.
Therefore, we've had a great deal of difficulty in enticing enlisted people to become members of the airport squadrons.
because they know that they'd be the first ones to go.
Civil engineering squadrons are the same way.
They're the guys that go out and build the dirt strips so that people can land in the forward group.
And so we've had a great deal of difficulty in manning civil engineering squads.
Now, I mentioned the recession.
When the recession came along, the manning is in direct proportion to economic conditions.
Anytime economic conditions are bad, you fill up the reserve program because it's not a bad
part-time job that pays to the point where it's significant now.
By the same token, if the economic conditions are good and everybody's vying for skills, then we're in the labor market like everybody else.
We try to hire our share of them, and we're not always successful.
Right now, we're fat.
That's not to say we will be six months or a year from now.
I was wondering about as far as recruitment during Vietnam.
I really wasn't that close to it.
And the reserves, I would have thought that many people would want to join the reserves so they could avoid active duty or the draft.
Well, I see what you mean.
Yeah, that's true.
That's always true.
And did you have that in the reserve units?
Long, long waiting list to get in reserve units, especially the Air Force reserve units now.
I understand even under those conditions that the Marine Corps reserves, the Army reserves really didn't have that many people wanting to get in a reserve program.
But the Air Force has always been
blessed in that people had rather, for some reason, had rather be in the Air Force than in the Army or the Marines.
That's not all people.
Some people prefer the Marines.

Now let's shift the conversation to women.
Women, of course, have flooded into the armed forces in the last 10 years in the active branch.
And it looks like I read a statement by the Department of Defense in which they're going to continue and even increase the percentage of women in the armed forces.
What impact has that had on the reserves?
We've had a number of women that have come into the reserve program in traditionally male specialties, primarily in the maintenance area.
Normally you'd think of an aircraft maintenance type as being a male, but we have a number of them that are training.
They're proficient.
They do an extremely good job.
When I say a number,
I don't think that the percentage is just real high.
But as far as I know, they're being recruited and trained and used in just about every career field I can think of in the Air Force.
What about attitudes?
I would say that initially, there's some resistance on the part of the male members of the reserve program
But that lasts a very short period of time, 30, 60, 90 days.
Then they're doing a job, and they're respected for the job they're doing.
And under field conditions, as far as I know, in any exercise we've had, there's never been any problem with, you know, rapes or anything like that.
I would say that there'd be no more problem in the military in a field exercise than there would be in any other exercise.
